			<item>
				<title>On facial recognition software: impact on local, state, and personal levels of privacy</title>
				<link>https://redzhift.github.io/articles/facial-recognition/</link>
				<pubDate>Thu, 11 Apr 2019 14:56:52 -0700</pubDate>
				<guid>https://redzhift.github.io/articles/facial-recognition/</guid>
				<description>&lt;blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Journalism article originally written in 2019, edited June 2026.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;→ &lt;strong&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;../facial-recognition-pdf&#34;&gt;PDF version available here&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; ←&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h1 id=&#34;intro&#34;&gt;Intro&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The first facial recognition systems of the 1960s were useless on their own. They required a human touch to identify and locate the parts of a face: ears, left and right eyes, nose and mouth.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://www.rhombussystems.com/img/face-detection-recognition.png&#34; alt=&#34;Various facial recognition points used in a security camera product by Rhombus.&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;em&gt;Various facial recognition points used in a security camera product by &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.rhombussystems.com/blog/rhombus-product-insight-%E2%80%93-face-detection-how-our-security-camera-system-captures-the-best-face/&#34;&gt;Rhombus&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
			</item>
	</channel>
